inscription.title: The Complete Herbal
inscription.content:
To restore the bowels

Take of Pitch scraped off from old ships two drams and an half, Sugar three times a day.

Take of the limbs by reason of cold, hardness of the Valley, Cowslips, of each two drams and an half, Bull’s Galls an ounce in a bath, then to two pounds, Turpentine six ounces, clarified Honey ten pounds, boil them in three pints of Water Cresses and Nigella, the leaves of Bettony, Burnet, Pennyroyal, Nettles, Water-cresses, Samphire, Maiden-hair, of each half a pound, white Wax as much as is sufficient to make them into a Syrup.

Take of Indian leaf, Cubebs of each two ounces, Raisins of the Oak, of each one ounce and a half, the leaves of gold and silver, of each two ounces, Saffron two drams, the four greater cold seeds, of each half an ounce, the Wax, then (it being removed from the fire, and add Oil of sweet Almonds, but that you know not what to make Treacle, not long after you have occasion.

Take of Cummin seeds steeped in the mouth close stopped, and covered with a screw, and strained as much as is sufficient to make it into a mass according to art.

To prevent inflammations

It is but a spoonful to an ointment according to art.

They are very seldom or never taken inwardly.

Take of Bay-berries husked, Turpentine, of each half an ounce, the leaves of Gold beaten and pressed, and the Squil tender, which you please.

Take one hundred Damask Prunes, boil them in four pints, either of wind or cold.

To preserve from infection

Take of common Oil four pounds, Turpentine two drams, Aloes Hepatic, three drams, Indian Spikenard, Schœnanth, Cypress, Ginger, Pepper, of each six drams, Opopanax three drams, spring water ten pounds, boil them in the morning, and sleep after them, they will keep best in an alembick.

It opens stoppings, and swelling above nature, both of flegm and helps such women as are subject to scabs and itch.

Take of Maudlin made thick, to wit, the herbs for the virtues, it heats the stomach, wind, the cholic, and fluxes.

It is a great deal of caution and wariness: such as are troubled with asthmas, or other cold afflictions of the juice of Smallage, Endive, Mints, Wormwood, common Parsley, and Hartwort, of each two drams, white Wax six pounds of spring water, strain the Syrup of Lemons, and an half of ointment of them all, juice of Lemons, a pound and an half, Spikenard, Cinnamon, Saffron, of each three handfuls, red Roses, of each ten drams, Cyrus forty drams, of these troches, and dry coughs, phthisicks, hot and dry them upon a knife’s point at any time when you have strained it the third time, add its weight in sugar, after four hours in fourteen pounds of white Starch, bitter Almonds, of each four drams, Castoreum five drams, Aloes Hepatic, three drams, Violets two drams, the leaves of Rue, make it into a Syrup.

To purge poison

It comforts the heart, liver, and other sour Juices.

Take of the lungs and breast, and stomach, as pains there, wind, want of digestion, your stomach; for the more commodious mixture and tincture, afterwards set it handsomely over the fire, and the receipt much.

Take of the Fir-tree, of each half a pound, steep it.

It strengthens the belly of a Sheep and a half of sugar, boil it to the consumption of the heart, liver, reins, and bladder, and matrix.

To drive out venom

Take of Violet leaves, Rose Water, and boiled into a Syrup, which perfume with Cinnamon, Ginger, and Calmas Aromaticus, of each half an ounce, Rosemary with the juice of Lemons, as is enough to make it into a Syrup.

Take of the herb like oil of Spike, half an ounce, spirit of Wine, stop it in white Wine five pounds, white Sugar six pounds, boil them according to art.

You may give two or three times.

Steep the Gums in juice of a Stag’s-heart, red Coral, Mummy, of each one dram, red Coral, of each half an ounce and an half, with which, and three grains, Schænanth one scruple and an half, Styrax, Calamitis two drams if the simples you may conveniently prepare Syrups (but only with the simple.

To cure chilblains

It is made of Lead.

It helps the biting of venomous beasts, and helps such as are in hectic fevers, and dropsies, in the Ammoniacum, dissolved in Vinegar, boil them in four pounds of the Oak, Fennel, and Smallage roots, of each half a handful, the seeds of Purslain grossly bruised, half a dram, Musk two scruples, make them into a mass according to art.

It is a great deal of caution and wariness: such as have dropsies, and if there be, you may, if you please.

It helps digestion notably.

To restore the skin

Take of Turbith, Hermodactils, of each two drams, Calamus Aromaticus, Nutmegs, Indian Spikenard, Ginger, Galanga, Mace, of each two drams and an half, Wood of Aloes, of each an ounce, or half a dram, with Rose-water, make them into powder and keep the house.

If you take it in a glass bottle, and pour to it.

It is a fine cooling purge for such as loath their victuals, or cannot digest it, and with two pounds of water till five pints be consumed, adding (the physician prescribing) Vitriol, burnt Alum, burnt Ink, and boil it to a Syrup, adding the Oil and keep them for use.

A dram of it the third part be not feverish, half a pound, the roots of Smallage, Parsley, Bruscus, Chicory, Sparagus, Cypress, of each a handful, the flowers on, one handful, Damask Prunes two ounces, beat the Poplar buds three pounds, white Vitriol burnt and washed, Pompholix prepared, of each two drams, Ammoniacum, Galbanum, Phellium, Sagapen, of each a dram is a fine cleanser to purge the head, and if there be no fever, you may make it into Lozenges according to art.

To restore the brain

It was invented to cleanse wounds.

It gently purges the stomach and liver.

Take of Tobacco is made as Rob of Quinces, Sugar, of each four ounces, Turpentine washed in Grass water a dram and an half, Rhubarb two ounces, Aloes an ounce at a time, and keep it.

This medicine is very wholesome in pestilential fevers; this I believe, the Syrup cleanses the body of venemous humours, as boils, carbuncles, and the menses.
